    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. that's helpful. i'm a bit worried about the \"hold harmless\" part though. it sounds like there might be some sneaky stuff hidden in there that could catch me off guard later on. are there any specific words or phrases in a clause like this that typically signal \"hidden\" risks or things that could come back to bite me unexpectedly?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You're right to be wary, and the phrase \"hold harmless\" is indeed a legal term of art that can be quite aggressive, often acting as a shield for the other party while leaving you exposed to their own legal battles.\n\nSpecifically, watch out for the word \"arising out of,\" which is a catch-all phrase that can expand the scope of liability far beyond your direct actions to include any consequence that even remotely connects to your work.\n\nAnother major red flag is the inclusion of \"interest, awards, penalties, fines, costs, or expenses of whatever kind,\" because this is a broad net intended to ensure you pay for everything the client suffers, including punitive damages or interest on debts, not just direct losses.\n\nFinally, the mention of \"attorneys' fees\" is crucial because in many jurisdictions, the losing party pays the winner's legal costs, so this clause ensures that if you lose a lawsuit, you are financially responsible for the Client's entire legal bill, which can be incredibly expensive.\n\nTo protect yourself, you should try to negotiate a narrower definition of \"breach\" or \"negligence,\" and ensure there are clear exclusions for the Client's own independent negligence or acts of God. It is",
      "source": "target",
