      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, you are absolutely right to stay hyper-vigilant, and these \"hidden\" liabilities often hide in plain sight using specific legal jargon that sounds harmless but carries a massive financial weight.\n\nOne common sneaky phrase is \"continuing indemnity,\" which means the obligation to pay doesn't end when the project is finished; it stays active forever if a lawsuit is filed years later regarding your work.\n\nAnother subtle trap is the \"retroactive\" or \"past acts\" clause, which allows the Client to sue you for mistakes you made months or even years ago, long after the contract has expired.\n\nYou should also look out for \"consequential damages\" or \"indirect losses,\" which can force you to pay for the Client's lost profits or business interruptions, not just the direct cost of fixing your error.\n\nFinally, watch for \"joint and several liability\" if you are working with other freelancers or vendors, as this could make you personally responsible for the entire bill even if only another party made the mistake.",
